Background and Context¶

You are a Data Scientist for a tourism company named "Visit with us". The Policy Maker of the company wants to enable and establish a viable business model to expand the customer base. A viable business model is a central concept that helps you to understand the existing ways of doing the business and how to change the ways for the benefit of the tourism sector. One of the ways to expand the customer base is to introduce a new offering of packages.

Currently, there are 5 types of packages the company is offering - Basic, Standard, Deluxe, Super Deluxe, King. Looking at the data of the last year, we observed that 18% of the customers purchased the packages. However, the marketing cost was quite high because customers were contacted at random without looking at the available information. The company is now planning to launch a new product i.e. Wellness Tourism Package. Wellness Tourism is defined as Travel that allows the traveler to maintain, enhance or kick-start a healthy lifestyle, and support or increase one's sense of well-being.

However, this time company wants to harness the available data of existing and potential customers to make the marketing expenditure more efficient. You as a Data Scientist at "Visit with us" travel company have to analyze the customers' data and information to provide recommendations to the Policy Maker and Marketing Team and also build a model to predict the potential customer who is going to purchase the newly introduced travel package.

Objective¶

To predict which customer is more likely to purchase the newly introduced travel package.

Data Dictionary¶

Customer details:

  • CustomerID: Unique customer ID
  • ProdTaken: Whether the customer has purchased a package or not (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Age: Age of customer
  • TypeofContact: How customer was contacted (Company Invited or Self Inquiry)
  • CityTier: City tier depends on the development of a city, population, facilities, and living standards. The categories are ordered i.e. Tier 1 > Tier 2 > Tier 3
  • Occupation: Occupation of customer
  • Gender: Gender of customer
  • NumberOfPersonVisiting: Total number of persons planning to take the trip with the customer
  • PreferredPropertyStar: Preferred hotel property rating by customer
  • MaritalStatus: Marital status of customer
  • NumberOfTrips: Average number of trips in a year by customer
  • Passport: The customer has a passport or not (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • OwnCar: Whether the customers own a car or not (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • NumberOfChildrenVisiting: Total number of children with age less than 5 planning to take the trip with the customer
  • Designation: Designation of the customer in the current organization
  • MonthlyIncome: Gross monthly income of the customer

Customer interaction data:

  • PitchSatisfactionScore: Sales pitch satisfaction score
  • ProductPitched: Product pitched by the salesperson
  • NumberOfFollowups: Total number of follow-ups has been done by the salesperson after the sales pitch
  • DurationOfPitch: Duration of the pitch by a salesperson to the customer

Preliminary Thoughts¶

The company has viable data that can be used to train various ML Models to predict how new packages should be marketed. However, we should keep in mind that the ML models will help us profile customers, but not tell us which customers would like to sign up for the Wellness Tourism Package specifically. This might create a bias that will not be captured by our model(s) because we do not know which customers would like the benefits of the Wellness Tourism Package. A way to capture that would be to assign weights to the five types of packages by considering which packages more closely match the benefits of the Wellness Tourism Package, and then train the model accordingly.

def display_missing(df):
    list1 = ['ProdTaken', 'Passport', 'OwnCar']
    print('Number columns:')
    cond1 = (df.dtypes == 'float64') + (df.dtypes == 'int64') # selecting float columns
    cond2 = df.isnull().sum() > 0  # selecting columns with NaN values
    cond_ = np.logical_and(cond1.values, cond2.values)

    for col_name in df.columns[cond1.values]:
        if col_name not in list1:
            a = df[col_name].apply(lambda x: x == 0).sum()
            b = df[col_name].isnull().sum()
            if (a != 0) or (b != 0):
                print(f"{col_name} has {b} NaN values and {a} zero values ")
    
    print('*' * 40)
    print('String columns:')
    cond1 = (df.dtypes == 'object')
    for col_name in df.columns[cond1.values]:
        a = df[col_name].eq('').sum()
        if (a != 0):
            print(f"{col_name} has {a} empty values.")

# taken help from Personal Loan Campaign solution sheet
def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count  = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1   = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(by=sorter, ascending=False)
    
    print(tab1)
    
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(by=sorter, ascending=False)
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 2, 6))
    plt.legend(loc="lower left", frameon=False)
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

  • Customer is more likely to take the product if they are single, than if they are married or divorced. This is probably because customer has less responsibility (cost of living is lower) when single, and also a trip would cost less since they likely only have to pay for themselves when single.

  • Customer with a higher monthly income is more likely to take the product.
  • Large Business Owners and Executives are more likely to take the product.
  • Passport holders are far more likely to take the product.
  • Customers who had a higher number of followups were more likely to purchase the product.

Model Building¶

We will build the following models:

  • Decision Tree
  • Random Forest
  • Bagging
  • Boosting
  • XGBoost
  • Stacking

Optimization¶

When predicting travel package purchases, we want to optimize the ML model such that the False Negatives are optimized. This is because if the model falsely predicts the customers who would purchase the product, i.e. the model classifies the "actual positive" as "negative", then this is loss of opportunity for "Visit with us." Whereas if the model falsely predicts the customers who would not purchase the product, i.e. the model classifies the "actual negative" as "positive", then worst case is that the product will be marketed toward the wrong customer, which would slightly increase the company cost. While comparing both scenarios, we conclude that loss of opportunity would be the greater cost, and hence we strive to optimize the recall score above other metrics.

# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
    """
    Check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables - Train set
    tr_pred = model.predict(X_train)

    tr_acc = metrics.accuracy_score(y_train, tr_pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    tr_recall = metrics.recall_score(y_train, tr_pred)  # to compute Recall
    tr_precision = metrics.precision_score(y_train, tr_pred)  # to compute Precision
    tr_f1 = metrics.f1_score(y_train, tr_pred)  # to compute F1-score
    
    # predicting using the independent variables - Test set
    ts_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    
    ts_acc = metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, ts_pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    ts_recall = metrics.recall_score(y_test, ts_pred)  # to compute Recall
    ts_precision = metrics.precision_score(y_test, ts_pred)  # to compute Precision
    ts_f1 = metrics.f1_score(y_test, ts_pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Train Accuracy": tr_acc, "Train Recall": tr_recall, "Train Precision": tr_precision, "Train F1": tr_f1,\
        "Test Accuracy": ts_acc, "Test Recall": ts_recall, "Test Precision": ts_precision, "Test F1": ts_f1},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
    """
    Plot confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    tr_y_pred = model.predict(X_train)
    tr_cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_train, tr_y_pred)
    tr_labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / tr_cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in tr_cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)
    
    ts_y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    ts_cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, ts_y_pred)
    ts_labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / ts_cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in ts_cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)
    
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12,6))
    
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    sns.heatmap(tr_cm, annot=tr_labels, fmt="", ax=axes[0])
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")
    plt.title("Train Set")
    
    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    sns.heatmap(ts_cm, annot=ts_labels, fmt="", ax=axes[1])
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")
    plt.title("Test Set")

Conclusions¶

Stacking Classifier has the best recall score of all the models (85%), but XGBoost Classifier has the best F1 Score (74%) on the test set. The models still seem to be overfitting, but not as much after we implemented Bagging, Boosting, XGBoost and Stacking.

The customer profile of those that purchase a travel product consists of:

  • having a passport.
  • Being single
  • higher monthly income
  • job designation of executive
  • receiving a longer pitch duration (but not too long); < 23 minutes
  • Younger age group

To improve the model, having data that alludes to which customers are interested in health and wellness would make the model more precise. With the current model, we assume that the predictions are biased in that the customer predicted to take the product is single and prefers the cheaper product - the Basic package. The current model does not take into account customer interests toward health and wellness, which is what the new product, the "Wellness Tourism Package" offers.

Some other thoughts that might help the company in helping more customers purchase the product would be to introduce aid/services in getting passports for customers who do not currently have them, offering family discounts and daycare services as part of the trip package to incentivize families to purchase the product, and fine tuning product pitches to optimize customer satisfaction.
